I disagree with Frank's claim that 16-year-olds are the safest drivers. 16-year-olds may have the fewest number of car crashes in total, but there are also less drivers at the age of 16 overall. I used the table to come to this conclusion. I have my math and answers following:

 

 


16 Years Old:  580.000/1.578.000

   =  0.3675538657  Crashes per Driver


17 Years Old:  702.000/2.195.000

                           =  0.3198177677 Crashes per Driver


18 Years Old:  710.000/2.432.000

                           =  0.2919407895 Crashes per Driver


19 Years Old:  670.000/2.652.000

                           =  0.2526395173 Crashes per Driver

 

Therefore, the safest teen drivers are 19-year-olds (~25%) rather than 16-year-olds (~37%). Crashes per driver decrease as the drivers get older, and more experienced.

data_answer: I disagree with Frank, because as a 16 year-old driver, there may be more restrictions for the person on driving. For axample, many 16 years old, depending on state, only have a driver's permit, not license. To obtain a driver's permit, one must take a course of driver's ed, get a pink slip, and finally take a written test. With a driving permit, there are many restrictions on when and how a person can drive. First of all, you must have six hours of driving lessons from and instuctor, and two of those hours must be at night. Also, when you practice driving, you must drive with an adult 25 years of age or older, and you must only drive at certain times, day or night. In addition to that, with a permit, you must complete 6 months of practice driving, with 50 hours in the day and 10 at night with an adult 25 years of age or older. Once someone gets their license, maybe even after your 16th birthday, you cannot drive with other passengers in the car unless they are 20 years or older until you have had your license for a year. As for siblings, you must have a written and signed note from your parents in order to take them anywhere. Therefore, 16 year olds have the least number of accidents because they have the most restrcitions when it comes to driving,

This creates an influx of completely new drivers out on the road, but some people may wait a little longer before trying to obtain their drivers license. Due to the gradually increasing number of drivers there are more accidents, but as time goes on those drivers who started anew are able to gain more experience in driving, thus causing less accidents. Frank believes that 16-year-olds are the safest drivers because they have the least number of accidents, but he also fails to realize that they also have the least number of drivers on the road.

 

16-year-olds may have the least number of accidents but they also have the least number of licensed drivers which would decrease the number of accidents related to 16-year-olds on the road since there are less 16-year-olds on the road compared to the other ages of drivers. Frank does not take into account the number of people on the road and the number of new drivers would correlate with the amount of accidents.

 

Due to the inability to think of the correlation, Frank is wrong in his assumption that 16-year-olds are the safest drivers on the road.

The accident rate better describes driver safety, as it shows a ratio, rather than a flat number of people, which Frank bases his assumption off of. By comparing ratios, one sees that the 16 year olds have an accident/license ratio of .36 (the highest), 17 year olds have a .32, 18 year olds have a .2919, and 19 year olds have a ratio of .25254 (the lowest rate). By observing the ratio of licensed drivers to the amount of accidents, one would find that the 19 year old age group is actually the safest group, and the 16 year olds are actually the most accident prone. I have to disagree with Frank, based off of this information. Franks statement would have been viable if each age group had the same amount of licensed drivers, though this is not the case. Since there is a different amount of drivers per age group, you must base your statements accordingly, and look at ratios, rather than comparing based off flat accident numbers.

Number of licensed drivers: 1,578,000
Number of accidents: 580,000
580000/1578000=.37 or 37%

Number of accidents: 702,000
702000/2195000=.32 or 32%

 

18-year-old drivers:


Number of licensed Drivers: 2,432,000
Number of accidents: 710,000
710000/2432000=.29 or 29%

 

19-year-old drivers:


Number of licensed drivers: 2,653,000
Number of accidents: 670,000
670000/2653000=.25 or 25%

 

    By looking at the data in the form of percents, we can see that Frank's clam does not hold any water. 16-year-old drivers have more accidents in ratio to the amont of teens who are driving; showing that they are not the safest teen drivers. They are in fact the most dangerous group of drivers. Looking at the data the older the driver is the less the percntage of them having an accident is. 19-year-old drivers are the least likely to have an accident at 25%. First:(numbers of licensed drivers) - (number of accidents) =(number of drivers that did not involved accident)

 

16 years old drivers:(1,578,000)-(580,000)=998,000

17 years old drivers:(2,195,000)-(702,000)=1,493,000

18 years old drivers:(2,432,000)-(710,000)=1,722,000

19 years old drivers:(2,653,000)-(670,000)=1,983,000

 

Second:(numbers of accidents) / (number of drivers that did not involve accident)=(the percent of drivers accidents)

 

16 years old drivers:(580,000) / (998,000)=0.58%

17 years old drivers:(702,000) / (1,493,000)=0.47%

18 years old drivers:(710,000) / (1,722,000)=0.41%

19 years old dribers:(670,000) / (1,983,000)=0.34%

 

In conclusion 19 years old drivers has the most less percent of drivers accidents.

data_answer: I disagree with Frank: 16-year-olds are not the safest teenage drivers, 19-year-olds are the safest teenage drivers. Because the numer of licensed drivers is not equal for all four age groups, the number of accidents cannot be directly compared to each other; the percentage of licensed drivers who get into accidents for each age group needs to be found. Although Frank is correct that 16-year-olds have the fewest number of accidents, the percentage of 16-year-olds who get in an accident is the highest of the four ages. If we divide the number of accidents for 16-year-olds and divide by the number of licensed drivers for 16-year-olds, we can see that around 37% of 16-year-olds get into an accident: 580000/1578000 = 0.37*100 = 37%. Repeating this process for the three other age groups, we find that 32% of 17-year-olds get into accidents, 29% of 18-year-olds get into accidents, and only 25% of 19-year-olds get into accidents. Therefore, Frank's claim is incorrect: 16-year-olds are actually the most likely age group of licensed teenage drivers to get into an accident, whereas 19-year-olds are actually the safest teenage drivers whom are least likely to get into an accident.
